So the point that I was making was this section of code in the EventManager

```
        foreach ($listeners as $listener) {
            if ($event->isStopped()) {
                break;
            }
            $result = $this->_callListener($listener['callable'], $event);
            if ($result === false) {
                $event->stopPropagation();
            }
            if ($result !== null) {
                $event->result = $result;
            }
        }
```

It makes it difficult to signal failure. If a listener returns false it stops propagation, but will not set the $event->result to false. The developer would have to maybe set $event->result = false and also return false.

I've been using exceptions in my listeners and this has worked better, but it's not directly supported by the EventManager

We could add some specific exceptions like `EventStopException` and `EventAbortException` that would be caught by EventManager and handled better.

@lorenzo I don't think `save()` can detect the state of a transaction after it has rolled back. Cake doesn't provide a transaction handle and there is no "is transaction still good" API for connections.

Also, what if `save()` was originally called after a transaction was started. Even if `save()` returns `false` this does not indicate that the transaction was rollback silently by a listener elsewhere. The caller is going to have the same problem that save is having now.

@ADmad I'm a little confused by this issue. If a `afterSave()` executed invalid SQL that would have produced a PDO exception from the driver. Even if it was a constraint violation. So how was the listener able to rollback the transaction but also silence any SQL errors?

Can we see a coding example?

> Again, I think we need to see code that demonstrates the issue as we're now getting into a debate about the problem, and there is nothing productive about that.

here it is:

``` php
function afterSave(...)
{
   $anyTable->save($invalidEntity); // This starts a transaction and executes rollback on failure
   ...
}
```
